document.title: Florida Early Learning and Developmental Standards: Birth to Kindergarten (2017)

AAA505B2BD0240B78F7AE7EAE63AFBAC.description:

that instruments and
art forms represent
cultural perspectives of
the home and the
community, now and in
the past

similar art forms

own art creations and
those of others

in individual and group
movement activities to

thoughts, observations,
imagination, feelings,
experiences and
knowledge

represents thought,
observations,
imagination, feelings,
experiences and
knowledge in individual
and group music

in a variety of individual
and group musical
activities

open-ended, processoriented and diverse art
materials

awareness of
technology and its
impact on how people
live (e.g., computers,
tablets, mobile devices,

things they need or
want

difference between
wants and needs

basic principles of
democracy (e.g.,
deciding rules in a
classroom, respecting
opinions of others,
voting on classroom
activities or civic
responsibilities)

problem solving and
decision making

expectations in varying
settings

take place over time in
the immediate
environment

within a sequence of
events to establish a
sense of order and time

relationship between
human decisions and

environment (e.g.,

conservation)

geographic tools and
resources (e.g., maps,
globes or GPS)

(e.g., far/close,
over/under and
up/down)

and similarities of basic
physical characteristics

features)

and similarities
between own
environment and other
locations

relationship of personal
space to surroundings

skills and roles (e.g.,
line leader and door
holder)

D64DFEBEBAF24F88BC2648B5DC7D0A6D.description:

awareness of group
rules (e.g., family,
classroom, school or
community)

groups within a
community

and similarities of self
and others as part of a
group

responsibility as a
member of a group
(e.g., classroom or
family)

8DB0A532125F41C09133FBF846EE28C7.description:

self is similar to and
different from peers
and others

characteristics of self as
an individual

attributes by comparing
and contrasting different
characteristics (e.g.,
language, literature,
music, arts, artifacts,
foods, architecture and
celebrations)

peers and families in
the classroom and
community

everyone belongs to a
culture

member of a culture

and constructs simple
objects or more
complex structures and
investigates concepts of
motion and stability of
structures (e.g., ramps,
pathways, structure,
Legos, block building
and play)

76BCDCBB449849E49690E7485522F008.description:

appropriate tools and
materials with greater
flexibility to create or
solve problems

why a simple machine is
appropriate for a
particular task (e.g.,
moving something
heavy, moving water
from one location to
another)

C3C6F9C0C0B6423AB3FC1AF47B101C50.description:
Identifies
problems and tries to
solve them by designing
or using tools (e.g.,
makes a simple tent
with a chair and cloth
for protection from the
sun)

D5D644C103EB47608EE411FA43E1E88B.description: Shows interest and understanding of how simple tools and machines assist with solving problems or creating objects and structures

examples of organized
efforts to protect the
environment (e.g.,
recycling materials in
the classroom)

routines demonstrating
basic conservation
strategies (e.g.,
conserving water when
washing hands or
brushing teeth)

people use objects and
natural resources in the
environment

appropriate vocabulary
to discuss climate and
changes in the weather
and the impact it has on
their daily lives (e.g.,
types of clothing for
different environments)

and nighttime cycle

explore and discuss
simple observations of
characteristics and
movements of the
clouds, sun, moon and
stars

sorts, compares, and
contrasts objects that
are naturally found in
the environment,
including rocks, soil,
sand and mud, and
recognizes relationships
among the objects (e.g.,
nature walks with hand
lenses, collection bag)
(e.g., rocks, twigs, leaves
and sea shells)

properties of water
including changes in the
states of water – liquid,
solid and gas (e.g.,
buoyancy, movement,
displacement and flow)

the relationship of
objects to light (e.g.,
light and shadows)

describes changing
states of matter —
liquid, solid and gas

78243852A9B640B7B2499929BE85C5E4.description:

the properties of an
object and the
properties of which the
material is made (e.g.,
water and ice)

predictions about how
to change the speed of
an object, tests
predictions through
experiments and
describes what happens

what makes objects
move the way they do
and how the movement
can be controlled

86F5B315F0304742B7E7576EC5647A91.description:

that living things differ
with regard to their
needs and habitats

FC2B562DCCA743CCB18F304CADF1C230.description:

distinguish between
living and non-living
things

living things grow,
change and go through
life cycles

the similarities and
differences among
various living things

Identifies
characteristics of a
variety of plants and
animals including
physical attributes and
behaviors (e.g.,
camouflage, body
covering, eye color,
other adaptations,
types of trees and
where they grow)

findings and outcomes
of experiments

form conclusions and
construct explanations
(e.g., What do the
results mean?)

C04EF910F7834785B476512134371A75.description:

and records data
through drawing,
writing, dictation and
taking photographs
(e.g., using tables,
charts, drawings, tallies
and graphs)

9F7C727EAC824ED882F36D3B1DFEF64B.description:

predictions and tests
their predictions
through
experimentation and
investigation

tools and various
technologies to support
exploration and inquiry
(e.g., digital cameras,
scales)

understand that
individuals may
experience sensory
events differently from
each other (e.g., may
like sound of loud noises
or feel of fuzzy fabric)

identify and make
observations about
what can be learned
about the world using
each of the five senses

each of the five senses
and their relationship to
each of the sense
organs

results of data collection

F10DE504E7C2420D91B48747E7259D00.description:
Represents, analyzes
and discusses data (e.g.
charts, graphs and
tallies)

Seriates (places
objects in sequence) up

cube towers or unit
blocks)

attributes such as length

problems by making
direct comparisons of
objects

nonstandard tools

move through space

relationships between
objects and locations

proximity (beside, next

over and under)

three-dimensional
shapes in the

castles in the
construction area)

putting two squares
together to make a
rectangle)

shapes using some

properties (e.g.,
vertices)

shapes (circle, square,

orientation

AB pattern using
different objects

a simple AB repeating
pattern

demonstrate how to
compose and

take apart) sets up to

fingers and acting out

dramatic play to solve
real-world joining and
separating problems

activities

number spoken tells

when counting objects

15 and beyond)

the number sequence “1
to 31”

without counting) up to
five objects

name, last name, or
nickname), not
necessarily with full
correct spelling or well‐
formed letters

letter‐like shapes or
letters to write words or
parts of words

scribbles/writing to
convey meaning (e.g.,
signing artwork,
captioning, labeling,
creating lists, making
notes)

answers appropriate
questions about the
story (e.g., “What just
happened?” “What
might happen next?”
“What would happen
if…?” “What was so silly
about…?” “How would
you feel if you…?”)

read aloud

shown a group of
letters, can accurately
identify, verbally or nonverbally, the letter

most letters (e.g., when
shown an uppercase or
lowercase letter, can
accurately say its name)

letters when named

group of letters, can
accurately identify,
verbally or nonverbally,
the letter that is named)

onset and rime to form

words to make a
compound word (e.g.,

words within spoken
phrases or sentences

Initiates
and participates in
conversations that
demonstrate
appreciation of printed
materials

A7672EE272164169BA41E6FA214D38F4.description:
Asks to be
read to, asks the
meaning of written text
or compares
books/stories

Interacts
appropriately with
books and other
materials in a print-rich
environment

0ACBAE159D334A5981D6186F9DFC179A.description:
Makes
real-world connections
between stories and
real-life experiences

4B78DD52B55749F2BE664C49F0633612.description:
Selects
books for reading
enjoyment and reading
related activities
including pretending to
read to self or others

D85D9BD7AB3842919BAFC30AC94EE782.description:
Matches
language to social and
academic contexts (e.g.,
uses volume
appropriate to context)

Demonstrates
knowledge of verbal
conversational rules
(e.g., appropriately
takes turns, does not
interrupt, uses
appropriate verbal
expressions and uses
appropriate intonation)

increased awareness of
nonverbal
conversational rules

responds to more
complex statements
and questions, follows
another’s
conversational lead,
maintains multi-turn
conversations,
appropriately
introduces new content
and appropriately
initiates or ends
conversations

F773BC2D813141708FA3C722B167E494.description:
Engages
in conversations with
two to three back-andforth turns using
language, gestures, and
expressions (e.g.,
words related to social
conventions like
“please” and “thank
you”)

0D0E4B7FE7394D429BA51AF0C1629E69.description:

sentences that give lots
of detail, stick to the

communicate intended
meaning

F48A17F31BC241BBB2D0A911A8AF34B3.description:

more than one idea using
complex sentences (e.g.,
sequences and
cause/effect
relationships)

Uses
sentences with more
than one phrase

regular and irregular
plurals, regular past

possessive pronouns

agreement

Typically
uses complete
sentences of five or
more words, usually
with subject, verb and
object order

E6D8348F72FC4880BCDD1FBBBC3219FC.description:

words in multiple
contexts, with the
understanding that some
words have multiple
meanings

Identifies
unfamiliar words asking
for clarification

0E5D789F796E46199E77853508F448A9.description:

variety of word-meaning
relationships (e.g., part‐
whole, object‐function,

large speaking
vocabulary, adding new

the meaning of many
thousands of words

social studies, math and
literacy), many more

uses (receptive

understanding of
functional and
organizational language

different, in front of and
behind, next to,
opposite, below) in
multiple environments

understanding of age‐
appropriate vocabulary
across many topic areas
and demonstrates a wide
variety of words and their
meanings within each
area (e.g., world
knowledge, names of
body parts and feelings)

E6670F37BFC2468B9D4C52F7143EC8FB.description:

and is understood by
both a familiar and an
unfamiliar adult but may
make some
pronunciation errors

two‐step directions
and usually follows
three‐step directions

ability to focus and
sustain attention, set
goals and solve
dilemmas presented in
conversation, story,
informational text or
creative play

the main idea, some
details of a
conversation, story or
informational text and

what is being learned to
own existing knowledge

understanding by
asking and answering
factual, predictive and
inferential questions,
